(675, 'Workshop Organizer Instructions', 'workshop-organizer-instructions', '', '<p> </p>\r\n<h1>Instructions for SPLASH''13 workshop organizers</h1>\r\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Thank you for your contribution to the SPLASH''13 program, workshops are an essential part of the SPLASH experience, and we will work hard to support you as best as we can.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">We will be needing some information from you at different points in time, below you can find an overview of deliverables.  Note that some of these are optional, depending on how you wish to organize your workshop.  The deliverables have to do with providing information about the workshop program, sending out a joint CFP, getting SIGPLAN sponsorship for those workshops that want to have ACM DL post-conference proceedings, and making the workshop program available before the early registration deadline.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">In addition, we will be using a shared data repository (a google docs spreadsheet) to keep track of information about each of the workshops, including your requirements, number of registrations, timing of significant events such as invited talks etc.  A link to this spreadsheet is circulated by email on acceptance of your workshop (please contact the chairs if you do not have the link).</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">In general, if you have any questions, comments or suggestions, please do not hesitate to contact the workshop chairs.</span></p>\r\n<h2><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">SUMMARY OF DELIVERABLES FROM ORGANIZERS</span></h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Organizational information (once your workshop is accepted):</span> \r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Scheduling constraints: Workshops are on Sunday October 27th and Monday October 28th, let us know if you have a conflict on one of those days, or if you have a conflict with another workshop.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Anticipated attendance: What is the expected number of participants (will be used for planning initial room assignments, if you do not have an estimate just let us know).</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Special requirements: Please identify any special requirements you might have, in terms of room configuration, audio and video equipment, etc.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Information for <strong>shared CFP</strong>: To have your workshop listed in the shared SPLASH workshops CFP, you must provide the relevant information to us by email, by <strong>May 15th</strong> at the very latest.  Please see "SHARED CFP" below.  <em>Please do not send individual per-workshop CFPs to SEWORLD (see below).</em></span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Optional: If you want <strong>ACM DL post-conference proceedings</strong> for your workshop, we need the information required for a SIGPLAN sponsorship application, by <strong>April 28th</strong> at the very latest.  (There <em>might</em> in addition be a second chance for applying at a later date.)  For details, please see "ACM DL POST-CONFERENCE PROCEEDINGS", below.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">For workshops with submissions: <strong>Workshop program decision</strong> must be posted on your workshop website at the very latest two weeks before the early registration deadline, that is, by <strong>September 17th</strong>.</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>SHARED CFP</h2>\r\n<p>The shared CFP contains information about each workshop.  Specifically, there is an overall introduction, then a summary of the workshops, and last the workshop abstract.  As an example, in 2012 the brief information for AGERE! was</p>\r\n<pre><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">AGERE! - 2nd Int. Workshop on Programming based on Actors, Agents, and<br /></span>Decentralized Control<br />organized by Gul Agha, Rafael Bordini, Assaf Marron and Alessandro Ricci<br />Submissions deadline: August 5 (abstract), August 12 (paper), 2012<br />http://agere2012.apice.unibo.it</pre>\r\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">The workshop abstract is normally taken from your proposal (let us know if you want something different), and is the same used to announce the workshop on the splashcon.org web page.  We need information on submission deadlines and workshop website, please send us this information by May 15th at the very latest.  We hope to have a decision on the ACM DL proceedings option by then, such that we can mention it in the shared CFP.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">The shared CFP will be sent to the following mailing lists: </span><span style="line-height: 1.3em; color: #000000; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10px;">seworld@sigsoft.org, </span><span style="color: #000000; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10px; line-height: 1.3em;">announce@aosd.net, </span><span style="color: #000000; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10px; line-height: 1.3em;">gpce-news@cs.rice.edu, </span><span style="color: #000000; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 10px; line-height: 1.3em;">ecoop-info@ecoop.org</span></p>\r\n<p>Note that since SEWORLD has a one-posting-per-event policy, a shared CFP is the only way we should publish workshop CFPs to this list.  Please let us know if you have suggestions for other lists that we should send it to.</p>\r\n<h2>ACM DL POST-CONFERENCE PROCEEDINGS</h2>\r\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Workshops can <em>optionally</em> select to have their proceedings published in the ACM DL, as separate proceedings.  For this to be possible, ACM SIGPLAN sponsorship is required, and we need to request this separately for each workshop that is interested in ACM DL proceedings.  We have been asked to submit all of the requests in one or if need be two packages, to faciltate processing by SIGPLAN, so please send it to us by email.  You can find details about it here:</span></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.sigplan.org/Resources/Proposals/Sponsored">http://www.sigplan.org/Resources/Proposals/Sponsored</a></p>\r\n<p>You need to provide information on items 1-11, either PDF or ASCII.  You do not need to provide financial information, except to mention that all finances are handled by SPLASH, so no need for a budget.  Some of the required information should already be there in your proposal, if in doubt please email us.  In addition to the sponsorship, approval of your program committee is also necessary, meaning that you must comply with the SIGPLAN diversity policy:</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.sigplan.org/Resources/Policies/Diversity">http://www.sigplan.org/Resources/Policies/Diversity</a></p>\r\n<p>The SIGPLAN sponsorship information <em>must</em> include a proposed list of PC members, quoting from Graham Hutton (previous SIGPLAN vice chair):</p>\r\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><span style="line-height: 1.3em;"><em>"Ensuring that the diversity policy is satisfied is one of the key aspects of the approval process, so we will need to have a proposed list of PC members for each workshop as part of their application.  Note that there is no need for invitations to have been sent out at this point.  Indeed, they should not have been sent out yet, as some PC''s may need to be revised to ensure that they satisfy the diversity policy (this is quite common.)  If it turns out that some events already have their PC in place, we still need to approve this, and perhaps add some extra members if some aspects of the diversity policy are not satisfied (in practice, it is usually geographical diversity that is the main issue.)"</em></span></p>\r\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Obviously, it is preferable to have a decision on the sponsorship before your call for papers can be published, which is why the sooner we get this information the better.</span></p>\r\n<p>Please send the application to us by April 28th at the very latest.  We have the option of doing a second round of sponsorshop applications, but this will only take place when the workshop program has been finalized, which might not be until July.</p>\r\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">The overall schedule is that SIGPLAN approval for the workshops and their PCs will be handled after April 28th.  A week after the SPLASH conference, you will be required to provide a final list of papers to be included in your proceedings, and the authors will in turn be required to provide final versions of their papers a month after the conference (November 30th).</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Note that we are currently not planning to do a shared ACM DL "SPLASH workshops" post-proceedings as was done for some workshops last year.  If there is demand for this we will of course reconsider, but since workshops can either go with the official SIGPLAN-approved proceedings or alternatively make their own or be part of a shared proceedings e.g. on arxiv.org, there does not seem to be a real need for this.</span></p>\r\n<p> </p>', '', 1, 0, 0, 0, '2013-04-03 21:42:21', 67, '', '2013-04-12 06:49:35', 70, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2013-04-03 21:42:21', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=0\nshow_create_date=0\nshow_modify_date=0\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 12, 0, 3, '', '', 0, 4062, 'robots=\nauthor='),
